Combined visit with The Monastery of SÃ£o Vicente de Fora
Apr 2023
The SÃ£o Vicente de Fora Church and Monastery are located at Largo de SÃ£o Vicente in the Alfama District and can be visited from 10am to 6pm daily. Entry is â¬5 per adult which includes the entire monastery as well as the ornately decorated back of the church. You can enter and view the front of the church around the main entrance for free.

Historically, the originally monastery was built in the 12th century after Dom Alfonso I liberated the city from the Moors. It was then dedicated to St. Vincent of Saragossa, whose relics were brought here at that time. However, the present church and monastery that you see today was built between 1582-1627 by Italian Jesuit and architect Filippo Terzi. It is Late Italian Renaissance in architectural style.

The church facade is three tiered with two bell towers flanking the entrance. You will notice a handful of niches fitted with statues of various saints. The interior is the shape of a Latin Cross with wide nave lined with side chapels. The ceiling is barrel vaulted and there is a huge dome over the crossing where you will find an impressive baldachin (canopy) by Portuguese sculptor Joaquim Machado de Castro.

As mentioned, you can enter the front of the church for free but can't proceed further to view the side chapels, high altar area up close. These are included (stop #5) as part of your self-walk tour through the monastery.

In the end, it's well worth the â¬5 spend to see the best parts of the church up close along with the full monastery. Note that you can also access the rooftop (stop #17) and walk around the outer dome on top of the church, taking in remarkable panoramic views of Alfama and surrounding districts of the city. Then carry on with other intended sightseeing around this area of Lisbon.
Written June 28, 2023

Saint Antonyâs Chapel
Nov 2022
This is a beautiful church and only accessible to visits if you enter the Monastery next door. One can enter the church through the front door, but will only have very limited access to the back of the church and not to the alter area. To the right of the alter (if you are facing it) you will find Saint Anthonyâs Chapel and his motherâs bones are buried there. The location of the chapel is where Saint Anthonyâs room was when he was a monk in the monastery next to the church. Saint Anthony was born in Lisbon and was an Augustine Monk before becoming a Franciscan Monk in Italy. He died in Padova Italy and was canonized there, hence St Anthony of Padova. Entry fee to the Monastery is â¬5.00 and it gives you visitorâs access to this church. Well worth the price. Most churches in Lisbon are not open for visits on Sundays, but this one is.
